{"id":"2201.05807","submitter":"Armando Pezo aP","authors":"Armando Pezo, Diego Garcia Ovalle, Aurelien Manchon","title":"Orbital Hall effect in crystals: inter-atomic versus intra-atomic\n  contributions","comments":"6 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.106.104414","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The orbital Hall effect (OHE) designates the generation of a charge-neutral\nflow of orbital angular momentum transverse to an initial charge current.\nRecent theoretical investigations suggest that transition metals display\nsizable OHE, encouraging experimental search along this direction. Nonetheless,\nmost of these theories assume that the orbital moment originates from the\nregion immediately surrounding the atom core, adopting the so-called {\\it\natomic center approximation}. In periodic crystals though, the contribution of\nthe interstitial regions is crucial and can lead to a severe misestimation of\nthe OHE. By applying the \"modern theory\" of orbital magnetization to the OHE,\nwe assess the relative importance of intra-atomic and inter-atomic\ncontributions in selected materials from first principles. We find that whereas\nthe OHE is mostly of intra-atomic origin for wide band-gap semiconductors\n(e.g., MoS$_2$), the inter-atomic contribution becomes crucial in narrow\nband-gap semiconductors (SnTe, PbTe) and transition metals (Pt, V etc.). These\npredictions invalidate the atomic center approximation adopted in some of the\nprevious works and open perspectives for the realization of efficient sources\nof orbital currents.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 15 Jan 2022 09:29:43 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 23 Jan 2022 20:59:02 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 9 Jun 2022 16:54:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-10-05"}
